classitems:[],plugins:[],extensions:[],plugin_for:[],extension_for:[],module:"Lights, Camera",submodule:"Camera",namespace:"",file:"src/webgl/p5.Camera.js",line:209,description:'\x3cp\x3eThis class describes a camera for use in p5\x26#39;s\n\x3ca href\x3d"https://github.com/processing/p5.js/wiki/Getting-started-with-WebGL-in-p5"\x3e\nWebGL mode\x3c/a\x3e. It contains camera position, orientation, and projection\ninformation necessary for rendering a 3D scene.\x3c/p\x3e\n\x3cp\x3eNew p5.Camera objects can be made through the\n\x3ca href\x3d"#/p5/createCamera"\x3ecreateCamera()\x3c/a\x3e function and controlled through\nthe methods described below. A camera created in this way will use a default\nposition in the scene and a default perspective projection until these\nproperties are changed through the various methods available. It is possible\nto create multiple cameras, in which case the current camera\ncan be set through the \x3ca href\x3d"#/p5/setCamera"\x3esetCamera()\x3c/a\x3e method.\x3c/p\x3e\n\x3cp\x3eNote:\nThe methods below operate in two coordinate systems: the \x26#39;world\x26#39; coordinate\nsystem describe positions in terms of their relationship to the origin along\nthe X, Y and Z axes whereas the camera\x26#39;s \x26#39;local\x26#39; coordinate system\ndescribes positions from the camera\x26#39;s point of view: left-right, up-down,\nand forward-backward. The \x3ca href\x3d"#/p5.Camera/move"\x3emove()\x3c/a\x3e method,\nfor instance, moves the camera along its own axes, whereas the\n\x3ca href\x3d"#/p5.Camera/setPosition"\x3esetPosition()\x3c/a\x3e\nmethod sets the camera\x26#39;s position in world-space.\x3c/p\x3e\n',
